newsitem.title: USA: NYMEX crude stalls at resistance, breaks support.
newsitem.headline: NYMEX crude stalls at resistance, breaks support.

text.p: NYMEX crude futures failed to break resistance early Wednesday then turned lower and broke through support, traders said.

The initial early bullish move came after the American Petroleum Institute reported late Tuesday that crude stocks fell last week. Further support came from below-expectations loading levels for November North Sea crude.

However, "the market just didn't have enough ammunition to push it higher today. When it could get through $25.70 it turned and broke through $25.35 (support)," said Tom Blakeslee of Cargill Investor Services. Tuesday's close was $25.42.

Blakeslee says he's targeting $24.80 as next support, which represents 61.8 pct Fibonacci retracement level. Nov crude was down as low as $24.90 by 1130 EDT/1530 GMT, having been as high as $25.70, equal to the post-Gulf War high set lat April (which was briefly broken in ACCESS trading Monday night).
But despite the turnaround in the market Wednesday, traders and analysts still see the market as staying bullish.

The American Petroleum Institute reported after markets closed Tuesday that crude stocks fell last week by 417,000 barrels to just below 302 million barrels. Ahead of the winter, the closely-watched heating oil stocks rose overall but were down in PADD I, the key northeastern market.

"The 673,000 bbls increase in distillate stocks (heating oil, diesel and jet) was within the range of expectations but there were some other eye-catching figures to give the data a stronger bullish spin," according to Tim Evans at Pegasus Econometric Group.

"Implied demand was heavy and may indicate renewed export activity...Furthermore, we think the market was braced for worse because of what happened last week and could see some buying today," Evans says in his daily report.
Heating oil November futures hit a high of 74.40 cents a gallon but sunk to a low of 71.35 on the reversal, before settling back up to 71.80 by just before midday.
Similarly, gasoline moved up to a high of 67.60 cents a gallon following crude, then slid to 65.25 before bouncing to 65.50.
